{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893786/1930111902/0341.xml":{"full_text":"She Snramsmlle Herald\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter in the Postofticc,\nBrownsville, Texas\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use\n(or publication of all news dispatches credited to it or\nnot otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nSubscription Rates\u2014Dally and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Year .$9.00\nSix Months 14.50\nThree Months *2.25\nOne Month .75\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas. Texas. 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo., 306 Coca-Cola Building.\nChicago, 111., Association Building.\nNeW York, 350 Madison Avenue.\nSt. Louis. 502 Star Building.\nLoa Angeles. Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg.,\n848 8. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Cal., 318 Kohl Building.\n\nBrownsville Has\n11\n1. A population in 1930 cf 22,030.\n2. A mean average temperature of 73.\n3. Bank deposits. S8.000.000.\n4. Four railroads, seven paved highways.\n5. International airport, five air lines.\n6. A $8,000,000 deep water port financed.\n7. The best climate, soil in the world.\nSeeking The Same Goal\nFriendship is a strange sort of thing. It appears,\nsometimes, where you would least expect it, and\nflourishes in spots where you would suppose that it\ncould find nothing whatever to feed on.\nSo it is with the friendship between Clarence Dar\nrow and Dr. Clarence True Wilson. It was revealed\nat Houston recently that these two men, who are in\npublic bitter foes on almost any question one can call\nto mind, are in private extremely warm friends. The\nwet. agnostic and the dry fundamentalist have de\nbated with each other a great deal and have traveled\ntogether a great deal; and somewhere they have\nfound a common ground, where mutual admiration\nand esteem can grow unchecked.\nDr. Wilson's discussion of the growth of this friend\nship is very much worth reading. It increases, some\nhow, one's respect for both men. He says;\n\"The fact is, if anybody can be a Christian without\nknowing it, I think it would be Clarence Darrow, for\nif you make a list of the Christian qualities which\na Christian ought to have, such as living according to\nthe Golden Rule, loving everybody, taking up for the\nones who need it most, standing against privilege\nand in favor of the unpriviliged. he lives what we\nteach as the best standards of life.\"\nThat, owning from a devout churchman to a man\nwho mounts lecture platforms to denounce religion\ncoining from a militant dry to one of the nation's\nmost outspoken wets, is a remarkable tribute, li\npoints to something that is of considerable import\nance; namely, that men can travel toward the sam*\ngoal by the most diverse roads, and that, they can\nmake the going smoother for themselves and other*\nIf they are broad enough to realize that there are. in\nthe old phrase, many paths to salvation.\nEach of these men has devoted his life to a baft\u2019e\nfor the truth as he has seen it. Each one has fought\nlustily for the sake of a cause. Each of them has\nbeen, and is. w\u2019hat we rail a visionary\u2014a man who\nhas caught a glimpse of the fair place that men might\nmake of this world if they only would, and who can\nnot rest until he has given all of his energy and all of\nhis strength to the expounding of his vision.\nOn the surface, they have been violently opposed.\nBut underneath? They are working toward the same\nend\u2014to make the world a more decent place, to re\nmove a bit of its sin and suffering and hopelessness\nto enable people to get more out of their lives in the\nshapp of happiness and the fulfillment of high de\nsires.\nIf the rest of us\u2014followers of one or the other of\nthese two men. or perhaps orrupants of the wid\u00ae\nmiddle ground between them\u2014could nnlv realize as\nthey have realized that we are. after all, seeking a\ncommon goal, even though we can't agree on the be^t\nmethod of getting there, wouldn't there be a good\ndeal less bitterness and misunderstanding in American\nlife today? 'And wouldn't tha* be an excellent thlr.f\nfor all of us? I\nIf -1\nThe Once Over\nBy H. 1. PH1LUPS\nHELP THE POOR BOOTLEGGER\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Associated Newspapers.)\nThe bootlegging business is in a depression. Never\nsince prohibition, according to reports, have the boot\nleggers had such a hard time making a dishonest\nliving.\n\nMany of them axe in such dire straits that they\ndon't know where the wife's next diamond necklace\nis coming from.\n\nThey are having a difficult struggle to keep the\nwolf from the labeling plant.\nm m\nUnless better times come very soon thousands of\nour best known bootleggers will have to give up their\nprivate yachts, get along with one limousine and sub\nlease their hunting estates.\n\nIn some cities the supply so far exceeds the de\nmand that they have stopped cutting the liquor with\nwater, industrial alcohol, piano polish and coloring\nextracts.\n\nDuring the prosperous era there was no industry\nthat boomed more than the liquor industry. The boys\ndidn't even have to send out salesmen. Orders pour\ned in over the telephone and all shipments were made\ncollect on delivery. The policy was never to give a\ncustomer an even break.\nThe only thing that flattened a consumer more\nthan the liquor Itself was the schedule of prices. If\nhe could survive both he was a Grade A insurance\nrisk.\n\nThe roar of the bootlegeers\" trucks was loud in the\nland and great was the prosperity of the poison ped\ndlers. Prices were subject to increase without notice\nand it was not considered cricket for a buyer to make\nany critical comment if he opened a bottle marked\n\u201cRare Old Parr Rvp\u201d and found it to contain raw\nturpentine.\n9 9 9 9\nNow all Is changed Buy Now\" would have been\na great slogan in the old saloon days but it is a dud\nas a business promoter in the alcohol industry.\n\nSince the market break of a jear ago the custom\ners have practically withdrawn in a body and con\nditions have reached a point where the bootleggers\nare almost ready to turn honest.\n\nThey are even ready to sell stuff in the original\nbottle.\n\nSome of the largest bootleggers are economizing to\nsuch an extent that they have closed their art de\npartments and are using only one design of label.\n\nThe boys are really in a bad wav. They could get\na better break selling apples on street corners. If\nthe situation gets any worse you may see the unprece\ndented spectacle of bootleggers in bread lines.\n\nAnd if you do we hope the bread they get is syn\nthetic and incorrectly labeled.\nMarked Down To 35 Cents\nThe bargain book lay on the counter forlorn.\nIts battered face covered with dirt;\nTo a very rude bookworm it said with a sigh.\n\u2022'I'm not angry but terribly hurt!\u201d\nAphasia.\nA kindergarten teacher came upon a little wa'f\nreaching into the bowl and squeezing a goldfish, and\nthen saving, ruefully. \"He don't go no more.\u201d\nPossibly what the stock market needs Is a theme\nsong replacing the old one known as \"I\u2019ve Got a Feel\ning I\u2019m Falling.\u201d\nSuggestion for another business revival slogan:\n\"Money makes the scare go!\u201d\nMovie Magazine\nPictures of some\nFamous stars.\nStories of their\nPas and Mas.\nGirls at whom the\nShieks all stare\nAnd a new star\u2019s\nUnderwear.\nL C. Chens\nOur Boarding House By Ahern\nI C5birL0V/&^ Vr\n\"TWE UiAV you SEE uM\nA5 TPE MAXTOR^ AS I 54iP U^LL\nSAVS Moui g* UM-M- PAV/ID, ABOLi\"T \"THE\n\"TME PRlAiCE A pAwJPOAi, I k/^6\u00ab5 S-fAMP\n'fEASlAiCLV nj?V MEAAi \u2019IS J COLLECT?OAl'\nREFERS \"To \u25a0>IgHaIE5S\u2018, S AUP,\nVOU A5 \"AiUBBV7) 15 A OMuIMiaIc/ VE5 \u2014Po/ViV\ny S c *Mp f -w yA TopcE-r -rPA-r\n\u2014-^\u2014J^TQUrfE r''\\ VOEEK-E AiP\n\u2018-AiOUi>COiViFlDEAi^Aa?4^7^H-^ ^/A UlE SPEAi-f\nSiP -TVIORivrrOAi ~*v WrTH 6E0P6E\nwill-The pri/vJce ^beraiarp sMauj j\nKiARRV, K\u2014X 7 T~HAlJ-PEAR\n4 QLD GEC&GiE\n*!0V\nw\u2014 u p*T orr.\nfcecepTToM -ro\\V\nSIR *\\j\nct*3b *t mca st*vicr \u2022\u2022tc if. )q\ntv C tu, N\u00a3A SEBVCE\nBEGIN HERE TODAY\nCelia Mitchell. 17. leaves Balti\nmore. where she has lived with her\nseamstress mother. Margaret Rogers,\nto join her father, John Mitchell, in j\nNew York. The parents are divorced\nand Mrs. Rogers is a widow follow\ning a second marriage.\nBarney Shields, young newspaper\nphotographer, is in love with the\ngirl Mitchell asks Evelyn Parsons\nbeautiful widow, to Introduce the\ndaughter to other young people. Mrs.\nParsons agrees, considering Celia\na means to win Mitchell's affections j\nShe soon becomes Jealous of the\ngirl and schemes to get rid of her\nby encouraging a romance between\nCelia and Tod Jordan, fascinating,\nbut of dubious reputation.\nMitchell has forbidden his daugh\nter to see Jordan. Shields comes\ni to New York to work for a photo\ngraphic service and meets Celia.\nShe tells him she cares for Tod Jor\ndan but later realizes it is Barney\nwhom she loves.\nMrs. Parsons goes to Mitchell and\ntells him the girl has been meeting\nShields surreptitiously. Father and\nj riauehter quarrel and Celia leaves\nfor Baltimore. Her mother is not\nthere and all clews to Mrs Rogers'\nwhereabouts fail. Mitchell arrives\nHe and Celia become reconciled\nand return to New York after he has\np-omised to locate Mrs. Rogers j\nMeanwhile. Mrs. Parsons invites\nShields to dinner and tells him Cel\nia is to marry Jordan. Next day\nCelia and Lisi go to a matinee and\nencounter Jordan. All three are\ntogether when they meet Shields.\nCelia leaves the others to talk to\nShields. The interview ends with\nthe understanding that all is over\nbetween them. That evening Mrs\nParsons announces to Celia that\nMitchell has asked her to marry\nhim.\nNOW GO ON WTTH THE STORY\nCHAPTER LIII\n\u201cYou mean\u2014!\u201d Celia began and\nthen she stopped From the ex\npression of Evelyn Parsons' face\nthere was no doubt that what the\nwoman had said was true.\nMrs. Parsons laughed and the\nsound was strident. I mean just\nvhat I said Evelyn continued.\n\u201cYour father has asked me to be his\nwife\u2014and I have accepted I must\nsav I'm disappointed. Celia. You\ndon't look very pleased!\u201d\nThe girl was staring at her. For\na moment she said nothing. Then\nr he leaned forward eyeing Evelyn\nappealingly and the words burst\nforth:\nBut I thought\u2014I mean when\nmother comes back\u2014oh. Evelyn, it\nwouldn't be right! You wouldn't do\nsuch a thing! Mother loves him\nstill. I know she does.\u201d\nEvelyn Parsons' shoulders strnigh\nj trned. \"So you disapprove!\u201d she\n1 said coldly. \u2018Really, my dear. I\ntlnnk it would have been more polite\nif you concealed your feelings. After\nall. your father and I are both\ngrown adults able to think for our\nselves. I had no idea you disliked\nme so much!\u201d\n\u201cOh. it isn't that! -Of course I\ndon't dislike you Please don\u2019t think\nme ungrateful for all you've done!\nBut don't you see what they both\nmean to me? Mother\u2014\u201d\n\"There Is no need for vou to sav\nany more And I shall tell vou\nI frankly that if your mother were\ni in this very room tonight begging\nme to give him up it would not alter\nmy plans in the slightest.. Do you\nthink Id let your father make a\nfool of hitr>Pr!f over tha* woman a\nsecond ime? Do you think T have\n!no feelings? No rights? Why do you\nt\"\ncling to this ridiculous notion that\nyour father and mother, separated\nwhen you were a child, would be any\nhappier together now? I tell you\nit s preposterous. They made one\nmistake, discovered it and parted\nDo you thiat you could possibly\nbring them together again? No!'\nMrs. Parsons' eyes flashed. Auger\nhad gotten the better of her usual\nsuavity. The exhibition of temper\nheld Celia spellbound.\n\u201cJohn and I love each other.\"\nEvelyn went on. \u201cIt will be useless\nor you to attempt to mterien*\nJohn's been devoted to me for years\nReallv, Celia, I should think you'd\nconsider his happiness even if you\ndislike me!\u201d\n\u201cYou mustn't say that. Evelyn. 1\ndo like you. It's just that it's such\na surprise. I was startled.\u201d\nm m\n\u201cBut why should you be surprised?\nSurely you must have known he\nwas fond of me. Why. I\u2019ve been\nputting him off for months! I had\nto respect Dw.ght's memory but it's\na year since he left me\u2014or practi\ncally a year. John and Dwight were\nsuch friends. That\u2019s one reason I\nfeel the hand of fate is guiding me\nOf course, it will be some time be\nfore the engagement can be an\nnounced You must promise me.\nCelia, not to speak of it!\u201d\nI won't tell anyone,\u201d Celia a\ngreed\n\u201cIt would mortify me fnght.fnlly\nif the news got out. Of course 1\nfelt that you should know at\nonce\u2014\u201d\n\u201cI'm glad you told me.\" the girl\nsaid slowly. I suppose it changes\neverything. d<5esn't it?\u201d\n\u201cWell, in some ways. In the\nfirst place I shall insist that John\nmust stop killing mimself in that\noffice. He's made himself a slave\nand it's because there's been no\none to guard his health and make\nhim take time for recreation. T'm\nplanning six months abroad im\nmediately after we re married. The\nO: ient would be a wonderful change\nfor him. don't you think so? I'm\nsure it would do him good. And\neverything will work out nicely be-\ncause you ran stay with your Rrand-!\nmother. I'm sure you'd prefer to\nbn in town anyhow and when we're\nhere we ll probably spend most of\ncur time at Larchwood Really. I\nthink it's only fair to you. You'll\ndevelop so much more without hav\ning us to depend upon.\"\nCelia was silent.\nMrs. Parsons had recovered her\ncomposure. After a moment she\nsaid softly: \u201cCelia, you're going to\nwish us happiness aren t you? Re\nmember, you're going to be marry- j\ning one of these days yourself.\u201d\n\u201cI wish on\u2014every happiness\nBut. my d*ar, you don't seem\nvery cheerful!\u201d\nThe girl's eyelashes lowered. \u201cI\nkeep thinking about my mother.\u201d;\nshe said. \"Father promised me\nhe'd do everything in the world\nto find her\u201d\n\u201cThen he'll keep his promise\nNaturally your father woulud not!\nallow the woman who was once his\nwife to remain in want. You know*\nhim well enough for that!\u201d\nFor an instant their eyes met\n\u201cDo you love him a great deal?\"\nCelia a'kcd tremulously\nOh. my dear\u2014if you only knew!\"j\nThe girl rose and walked to the\nwindow which faced westward. She\ncould stand there with her back\ntoward Evelyn pretending to look\nout at the nirhi until she forced\nthe t^ars back Th^re were great\nhot drops on her cheek. Celia\nTh\u00a7 Main Stem\nIntimate Glimpses of the Valley\u2019s Alley\nBY J. R.\nAlong Elizabeth One Embarrassing Moment Gun Blows t*p\nA Blushing Violet Our Sports Editor About\nSmuggling And A Baby Austin.\nAlong Elizabeth\nJesse Dennett.of Dennett\nMotor company....dressed in the:\nheight of fashion-walking along\n...Gordon Street...youngest bank,\npresident in the state of Texas....\ntalking to Doc Osborne and Knight\nDouglas_a couple of henchmen j\n_the former a football official.1\nthe latter an A-l publicity man...\nJohn Crum_of the Rio Grande\nValley Gas company.arguing\nwith Officer Lozano about his in\ntentions in parking a car near a\n\"No Parking\" sign-Mr. and Mrs.!\nJohn E. Rutledge of Edinburg\n_in Brownsville on a visit Tues-\nday_left the chilluns at home..\n...Jimmy George.crack golfer1\nand sportsman... now game w arden\nI.warns hunters not to kill\n1 curlews_says that the idea sea\nson is open on them is erroneous..\n..hunter beware... Johnny Mein- i\nnis listening to a photograph\nrecord_Jesus Flores standing near\nhoping to tell it to him his I\nhopes were in vain-Johnny ap\nplauded and walked out-Miss\nMalvina Garibay.chamber of\ncommerce employe talking to a\nmember of th* Brownsville police\nI force.later driving a brown\nj sedan.\nBad Business\nJohnny Puckett is a Rood hunter.\nHe knows how to track deer, knows\nthe Rood places to get ducks and\ngeese. 1\nBut sometimes he has bad luck.\nIn fact, he had rotten luck about\ntwo weeks ago.\nHe was out in the brush hunting\n\u2014not deer, of course, for the sea\nson wasn't opened\u2014a n d wasn't\nhaving much luck of the right kind.\nThen, all of a sudden, he had a\nchance for an excellent shot.\nHe threw the gun to his shoulder\ni and pulled the trigger. The result\nwas a terrible explosion and the t\ngun curled up in his hands\nUnfortunately he had gotten\nsome mud in the barrel.\nStickler Solution j\nIf the professor spends $900 more\nthan one-half his earnings each\nyear and saves $3000 in five years\nlor $000 earh year! his earnings\namount to one-half his money,\nplus $900 plus $600. Therefore\n$909 plus $609 would be the other\nl,,l\u00bb V.1* mnn*\u00ab in<l his tCtll\ni\nHowever, he was lucky in one j\nrespect\u2014he wasn't seriously Injured I\n\nBlushing Violet\nThus is really a subject for the\nsports editor, but it happens to be\nabout the sports editor himself and\nhe's too modest to say anything\nabout it.\nHal Eustace. Herald sports editor,\nis the only person ever to shoot a\nperfect score on a local bowling\nalley.\nThat'.s what Billy Burnett said,\nand Mr. Eustace admitted that he\nmade a perfect score, blushing\nmeanwhile.\n\nViolets will be violets.\nm m m\nSmuggling\nAn Associated Dispatch in Tues\ndays Herald told of booze smug-\ngling up near Detroit by eirplane.\nAccording to the story, the smug\nglers were using about 30 planes.\nWhich recalls to our mind that\nabout three years ago a friend of\nours, who was an aviator, was ap\nproached with a similar offer from\na Texas syndicate, to fly \u2019xxize\nacross the border and land near\nCorpus Christi. The pay was\nlucrative but the man's conscience\nwas stronger He was offered about\nSI.000 a month, a plane, and all he\nhad to do was fly twice a week. At\nthe leading end. men would load\nhis plane, and when he landed in\nthe United States, others would\nunload it.\nBut. he turned the ofter down\nflat.\nIt's highly pcssibie. though, that\nsomething of this nature is going\non right now. What can be done\nabout it? Not much, we guess.\n\nAustin Goes Boom\nMonday night one of those baby\nAust ..n cars was subjected to rather\nrough treatment in Matamoros\nThe owner had left it parked on\nthe street while he went inside to\ngobble pretzels, and a crowd\ngathered around the r r\u00bbt auto.\nSeveral began testing their power\nbv lifting the car. One didn't know\nhta awn strength and the car fell\non its side. And that's the position\nIt was In when the owner found\nit later.\nIf we owned an Austin, we\nwouldn't fee! badly about that\nWhat would worry us. though,\nwould be the fear that som\u00ab heftv\nindividual would pick it uo and\ntake it home for the kiddies to\nplaj with. j\n_\u2014-\u2014-\u2014V\nI Out Our Way.By Williams\nBCmE OF TViEM U\ns.oovmnj ew th* t\n3AD X WA\u00ab> GOikj\u2019 Y\nBur f^E^S MO\nT*-\\\u2018 FlRE MEM h\nE GOT \u00bbr wEAnuVJ=\njT mow.\nthp o\\1 mavj to be\n_woof? FAVOPIT^ HERO\nei\u00abc\u00bbrwu n>ivici \u00bbtc\nbrushed them aside casually. Then\nshe turned.\n*T didn't make plans for the eve-,\nrung,\" Mrs. Parsons said, glancing1\nup.; because I thought it would\nmean a great deal to both of us to.\nkeep it uninterrupted. It makes\nme happy to know you're looking\na- the situation unselfishly.\u201d\nThe dart found its target.\n*'I suppose I have been selfish.\u201d.\nCelia admitted, \u201dbut I didn't mean j\nto be! I must see father tomorrow\nand congratulate him.\u201d\nEvelyn started. Oh. r.o' Prom\nise me you won't do that.\" she ex\nclaimed. \"You see. dear, I have a\nconfession. Your father wanted to\nb\u00ab the first to fell you the news. I\nI agreed but afterward when he\nsaid he didn t want you to know\nuntil just before the announcement\nwas made public I felt he was\nwrong. That's why I made up my\nmind to tell you myself. Of course,\nyou can't blame John' He doesnt\nunderstand how a girl would feel\nabout such a thing.\u201d\n\u201cOh. I see.\u201d\nft ft ft\nThe quick glance of Evelyn Par\nsons was apprehensive. \"You are\nglad I told you, aren't you?'* she\nasked.\n\u201cOf course\n\u201cI was sure of It. It's Just the\nsort of thmc you couludn t expect 1\na man to understand. And when\nhe tells you himself you won t let\nh:m dream you suspected, will you?\" i\n\u201cWell. I ll do the best I can to\nkeep him from guessing.\u201d\n\u201cThat\u2019s a dear girl. You see. you\nand I must stand together. And\nwe re going to! Give me your word\nCe\u2019ia. that you won\u2019t mention any\nthing I\u2019ve said to your father.\u201d\n\u201cWord of honor.\u201d\nEvelvn heard a little sigh and\nsmiled. \u201cI wonder what I did with\nthat book on rontract bridge that\nFannie loaned me.\" she said after\nan interval. \u201cHave yau seen it\nanywhere?\"\nCelia shook her head. \u201cI'll heip\nyou look.\u201d she offered.\nShe did not prove useful in the\nscorch. Mrs Parsons found the\nvolume without assistance and set\ntlec down with it before a reading\nlamp. Celia chose a magazine and\ncurled up on the davenport. She\nopened the pages and looked down\nat them but the lines of type might\nhave been invisible. She neither\nread nor saw them. Her hands\nwere icy and Celia clenched them\ntogether. The pain in her heart\nhad begun agaim\nEverything was lost. Everything,\nin the world that she cared about\nwas gone. With Barney beside her\nCe\u2019ia felt she could have faced her\nfather's remarriage, even though it\nsevered ties from Margaret Rogers\nNow\u2014what was there left?\nAt the earliest possible moment\nthe girl excused herself. Before she\nleft the room Evelyn Parsons drew\nCelia down beside her and kissed\nthe girl's forehead. \u201cHappy dreams,\ndear!\u201d she said smiling.\n\u201cGood night!\u201d Celia replied and\nwent to her bedroom.\nShe undressed and got into bed\nbut she could not sleep It was\ntoward dawn when at last she drift\ned off into troubled slumber. Con\nsequently she awoke late next morn\ning and there were shadows under\n\u2666he brown fyes.\nAfter she had breakfasted Celia\nmoved about restlessly At 11\no'clock she put on her hat. and told\nMrs. Parsons she was going for a\nwalk.\n\u201cOrder lunch for whenever you\nlike.\u201d Evelyn called. \"I shan't be\nhere\u201d\nCelia\u2019s answer was an Inaudible\nmurmur as she let herself out of\nthe apartment. She took the ele\nvator to the street and walked to\nFifth avenue. There she mounted\na bus and rode to the building\nwhere John Mitchells law office\nwas located Celia had been there\nor.lv twice before.\n\nShe gave her name to the girl in\nthe reception room Five minute;\nlater a tall, dark-haired young\nwoman appeared smiling She was\nJohn Mitchell's secretary\n\u201cMiss Mitchell?\u201d the young wo\n\nJUICY STEAK SUPPER\n50c\nAnthony's Waffle j\nShop\n517 12 St. Phone 983\nman said approaching Celia. \u201cI'm\nsorry. Your father isn't in.\"\nOh!\"\n\u201cIs there anything you'd like to\nhave me tell him?\u201d\n\u201cWhen do you think he'll be\nback?\"\nWell, really, its doubtful. Its\nalmost noon now and he has a\nluncheon engagement. I don't know\njust when to expect him.\"\nCelia had had enough business\ntraining to know that confidential\nsecretaries were likely to be thor-1\noughl.v informed on their employ\ner.' personal as well as professional\naffairs. Miss Roberts who stood be\nfore her. was a confidential secret\nary.\n\"Could T come into your office for\na minute?\" Celia asked\nThe two went into a small inner\nroom. Celia hesitated. Then she\nsaio nervously. \"You probably\nknow father's trying to locate my\nmother. Has there been any word\nvet?\"\nA look of quirk sympathy crossed\nthe older girl's face. She shock\nher head.\nWe haven't heard anything yet.\"\ndhe said. \"He was expecting a\nmessage all day yesterday but it\ndidn't come I'm sure he'll let you\nknow as soon as there is anything\ndefinite.\"\n\"Then I guess that's all. Thank\nyou very much.\u201d\nCelia turned and left the office.\nShe rode uptown and returned to\nthe apartment. She was there at\n10 minutes after three that after\nnoon when the maid announced\nthere was a young man to see her.\n(To Continued!\nThe total number of counties in\nthe United States is 3070. The total\ndoes not include 22 independent\ncities.\nTelephone\n123\nFor prompt, efficient\nand considerate am\nbulance service.\nHINKLEY MORTUARY\n\u201cBrownsville\u2019s Funeral Home\u201d\nCOURTESY\n,7b Smallest Depositor\nThe First National has found it\ngood business to .extend the fullest\ncourtesy to the smallest depositor\nand has been doing so since 189L\nThat\u2019s why we are rrowing day by\nday...\nFirst National Bank\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\nWOOD and DODD\nInsurance Surety Bonds V _\nspivey Kowalski Bldg. 1\nBROWNSVILLE OAR C","height":"36204","width":"27840"}}
